00:13:15.370 --> 00:13:17.680 align:middle line:84%
that the snowflake
actually occupies

00:13:17.680 --> 00:13:19.780 align:middle line:90%
remains relatively constant.

00:13:19.780 --> 00:13:22.600 align:middle line:84%
All of those ideas now I'm
going to bring them together

00:13:22.600 --> 00:13:26.500 align:middle line:84%
to answer the question, how
long can our simulation last.

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:28.750 align:middle line:90%
What would cause it to end?

00:13:28.750 --> 00:13:30.910 align:middle line:84%
In a simulation
environment, when

00:13:30.910 --> 00:13:33.100 align:middle line:84%
we ask ourselves
what could possibly

00:13:33.100 --> 00:13:37.590 align:middle line:84%
end this virtual reality,
this world that we know,

00:13:37.590 --> 00:13:41.600 align:middle line:84%
the end would be the same as
it is for any computer program.

00:13:41.600 --> 00:13:44.750 align:middle line:84%
When one of two possible
conditions exists,

00:13:44.750 --> 00:13:47.110 align:middle line:90%
the end of the program occurs.

00:13:47.110 --> 00:13:50.050 align:middle line:84%
Number one is when
the system runs out

00:13:50.050 --> 00:13:54.520 align:middle line:84%
of space to store the
information that is generated.

00:13:54.520 --> 00:13:57.610 align:middle line:84%
Number two is when
something unexpected

00:13:57.610 --> 00:14:01.070 align:middle line:84%
happens that corrupts
the entire system.

00:14:01.070 --> 00:14:03.070 align:middle line:84%
So let's take a
look at these two

00:14:03.070 --> 00:14:06.640 align:middle line:84%
very well-known possibilities
for conventional computer

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:07.690 align:middle line:90%
programs.

00:14:07.690 --> 00:14:10.150 align:middle line:84%
And let's see how
they might apply

00:14:10.150 --> 00:14:14.860 align:middle line:84%
and what they may mean for
our simulated environment.

00:14:14.860 --> 00:14:19.600 align:middle line:10%
Before his death in 2008,
Princeton University Professor,

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:23.410 align:middle line:10%
John Wheeler, a physicist, he
was a contemporary of Albert

00:14:23.410 --> 00:14:24.830 align:middle line:10%
Einstein's.

00:14:24.830 --> 00:14:28.810 align:middle line:84%
But he and Albert Einstein
had very, very different ideas

00:14:28.810 --> 00:14:32.050 align:middle line:84%
of our relationship to
our physical reality.

00:14:32.050 --> 00:14:35.800 align:middle line:84%
Nothing could have been
more diverse than the way

00:14:35.800 --> 00:14:39.100 align:middle line:84%
that these two men, looking
at the same information,

00:14:39.100 --> 00:14:41.480 align:middle line:84%
the same data,
the same formulas;

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:44.050 align:middle line:84%
fought about our
relationship to the world.

00:14:44.050 --> 00:14:47.740 align:middle line:84%
And they came up with very,
very different perspectives.

00:14:47.740 --> 00:14:50.260 align:middle line:10%
Albert Einstein,
brilliant man that

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:55.990 align:middle line:10%
was, he did not like the idea
that we could be so deeply

00:14:55.990 --> 00:14:59.260 align:middle line:10%
connected with our environment
that we could actually

00:14:59.260 --> 00:15:03.580 align:middle line:10%
influence our environment
and especially at a distance.

00:15:03.580 --> 00:15:07.510 align:middle line:84%
Albert Einstein did not like
the idea of entanglement.

00:15:07.510 --> 00:15:11.140 align:middle line:10%
These theories were just being
developed during his lifetime.

00:15:11.140 --> 00:15:13.930 align:middle line:10%
And when he heard that
it may be possible

00:15:13.930 --> 00:15:16.645 align:middle line:10%
for us to influence
from where we

00:15:16.645 --> 00:15:18.520 align:middle line:10%
are one part of the
world to what's happening

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:20.228 align:middle line:10%
in another part of
the world, he actually

00:15:20.228 --> 00:15:22.490 align:middle line:10%
have a term for that
kind of influence.

00:15:22.490 --> 00:15:25.810 align:middle line:84%
He called it spooky
action at a distance.

00:15:25.810 --> 00:15:27.370 align:middle line:90%
Einstein didn't like that.

00:15:27.370 --> 00:15:30.790 align:middle line:84%
And he went to his
grave with a frustration

00:15:30.790 --> 00:15:34.300 align:middle line:84%
of never being able to
unify the laws of physics,

00:15:34.300 --> 00:15:36.685 align:middle line:84%
because he did not allow
for this relationship,

00:15:36.685 --> 00:15:39.680 align:middle line:84%
this entanglement that
we see in our world.

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:40.680 align:middle line:90%
This is on the one hand.

00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:42.840 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand,
John Wheeler came up

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:46.290 align:middle line:84%
with a completely different
view of the universe.

00:15:46.290 --> 00:15:49.860 align:middle line:84%
Wheeler said the universe
could not exist without us.

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:53.730 align:middle line:84%
He said that we are part
of an ongoing process.

00:15:53.730 --> 00:15:55.920 align:middle line:84%
He said the universe
isn't finished yet.

00:15:55.920 --> 00:15:59.430 align:middle line:84%
He said it is
continually being built.

00:15:59.430 --> 00:16:01.890 align:middle line:84%
We are continually
adding to the universe

00:16:01.890 --> 00:16:04.410 align:middle line:84%
and we're doing it
through consciousness.

00:16:04.410 --> 00:16:06.830 align:middle line:10%
He said, we live
in what he called--

00:16:06.830 --> 00:16:10.590 align:middle line:10%
and I'm going to quote-- "a
participatory universe that

00:16:10.590 --> 00:16:13.100 align:middle line:10%
continues to build itself."

00:16:13.100 --> 00:16:15.770 align:middle line:10%
Well, the implications
of what John Wheeler said

00:16:15.770 --> 00:16:18.330 align:middle line:10%
have a direct
impact on the answer

00:16:18.330 --> 00:16:20.895 align:middle line:10%
to the question, how long
can our simulation last.

00:16:20.895 --> 00:16:23.650 align:middle line:90%
And here's the reason why.

00:16:23.650 --> 00:16:26.220 align:middle line:84%
What John Wheeler said
to us about living

00:16:26.220 --> 00:16:30.000 align:middle line:84%
in a participatory universe
suggests the following.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:34.020 align:middle line:84%
It suggests that we
will probably never find

00:16:34.020 --> 00:16:39.480 align:middle line:84%
the smallest particle of
matter, because every time we

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:45.090 align:middle line:84%
peer deeper and deeper
into the fundamental nature

00:16:45.090 --> 00:16:46.395 align:middle line:90%
of our reality--

00:16:46.395 --> 00:16:48.390 align:middle line:84%
and this is what's
important here--

00:16:48.390 --> 00:16:54.920 align:middle line:84%
the act of us looking is an act
of creation in our simulation.

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:58.320 align:middle line:84%
And it puts something
there for us to see.

00:16:58.320 --> 00:17:00.660 align:middle line:84%
So, the deeper we look,
every time scientists

00:17:00.660 --> 00:17:02.710 align:middle line:84%
think they've got the
smallest particle,

00:17:02.710 --> 00:17:04.410 align:middle line:84%
then they build new
equipment and they

00:17:04.410 --> 00:17:06.240 align:middle line:84%
find that they can
break that particle

00:17:06.240 --> 00:17:08.631 align:middle line:84%
and there's something
underlying that particle.

00:17:08.631 --> 00:17:11.089 align:middle line:84%
And then they do it again, and
they do it again, and again.

00:17:11.089 --> 00:17:14.970 align:middle line:84%
Now think about what this means
in terms of our simulation.

00:17:14.970 --> 00:17:18.950 align:middle line:84%
Every time we look and
consciousness puts something

00:17:18.950 --> 00:17:24.300 align:middle line:84%
there for us to see that
something is energy.

00:17:24.300 --> 00:17:26.280 align:middle line:90%
It is information.

00:17:26.280 --> 00:17:31.950 align:middle line:84%
And we are constantly adding
information to the system

00:17:31.950 --> 00:17:35.460 align:middle line:84%
through the act of
looking, searching,

00:17:35.460 --> 00:17:38.100 align:middle line:84%
to find the limits
of our experience.

00:17:38.100 --> 00:17:40.800 align:middle line:84%
So, the deeper we look into
the atom, the more information

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:42.060 align:middle line:90%
we're putting out there.

00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:44.280 align:middle line:84%
The further we look
into the cosmos,

00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:47.070 align:middle line:84%
scientists are looking for
the edge of the universe.

00:17:47.070 --> 00:17:49.440 align:middle line:84%
And they thought
they found it twice.

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:51.810 align:middle line:84%
They thought they
found the boundary that

00:17:51.810 --> 00:17:54.955 align:middle line:84%
marks the edge of our
physical universe.

00:17:54.955 --> 00:17:55.830 align:middle line:90%
Here's what happened.

00:17:55.830 --> 00:17:57.450 align:middle line:90%
They built new equipment.

00:17:57.450 --> 00:18:00.360 align:middle line:84%
And the new equipment
looked differently

00:18:00.360 --> 00:18:03.144 align:middle line:84%
at that boundary
and lo and behold,

00:18:03.144 --> 00:18:04.810 align:middle line:84%
they found that there
was something else

00:18:04.810 --> 00:18:07.080 align:middle line:90%
beyond the boundary.

00:18:07.080 --> 00:18:09.420 align:middle line:90%
I can't emphasize this enough.

00:18:09.420 --> 00:18:14.700 align:middle line:84%
Our act, the act of us
looking with the expectation

00:18:14.700 --> 00:18:19.050 align:middle line:84%
that we will see something,
is an act of creation

00:18:19.050 --> 00:18:21.840 align:middle line:90%
within our simulated universe.

00:18:21.840 --> 00:18:25.980 align:middle line:84%
And the more we create, the more
information we are generating.

00:18:25.980 --> 00:18:28.710 align:middle line:84%
And that information
has to go somewhere.

00:18:28.710 --> 00:18:34.310 align:middle line:84%
We are living in a finite
environment of our simulation.

00:18:34.310 --> 00:18:36.940 align:middle line:84%
And this is what the Koch
snowflake was telling us.

00:18:36.940 --> 00:18:40.860 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, how
much can we explore?

00:18:40.860 --> 00:18:43.470 align:middle line:84%
How much information
can we create?

00:18:43.470 --> 00:18:47.100 align:middle line:84%
How much energy can we
generate until our environment

00:18:47.100 --> 00:18:49.800 align:middle line:90%
is full and can hold no more?

00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:52.710 align:middle line:84%
And when we reach
that point, and I

00:18:52.710 --> 00:18:54.270 align:middle line:84%
don't know if it's
in the near future

00:18:54.270 --> 00:18:56.150 align:middle line:90%
or in the distant future.

00:18:56.150 --> 00:18:59.900 align:middle line:84%
But what the fractal code tells
us is that at some point--

00:18:59.900 --> 00:19:01.680 align:middle line:90%
remember the Koch snowflake.

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:05.930 align:middle line:84%
It said we can
generate complexity.

00:19:05.930 --> 00:19:07.875 align:middle line:84%
But when it comes
to the actual space

00:19:07.875 --> 00:19:10.110 align:middle line:84%
that the snowflake
takes, it levels out.

00:19:10.110 --> 00:19:12.630 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't go on forever.

00:19:12.630 --> 00:19:17.340 align:middle line:84%
When we reach that level that
suggests that our simulation

00:19:17.340 --> 00:19:18.647 align:middle line:90%
would come to an end.

00:19:18.647 --> 00:19:20.730 align:middle line:84%
And this is really
interesting, because scientists

00:19:20.730 --> 00:19:22.710 align:middle line:84%
are telling us now
that we are doubling--

00:19:22.710 --> 00:19:26.620 align:middle line:84%
doubling the amount of
information that comes to us.

00:19:26.620 --> 00:19:30.450 align:middle line:84%
And at least every year we are
doubling what we have known.

00:19:30.450 --> 00:19:33.570 align:middle line:84%
It took 5,000 years
for the first doubling.

00:19:33.570 --> 00:19:35.850 align:middle line:84%
And now the second
and third and fourth

00:19:35.850 --> 00:19:37.890 align:middle line:90%
we're doubling every year.

00:19:37.890 --> 00:19:40.470 align:middle line:84%
So it means that we are
generating more information,

00:19:40.470 --> 00:19:42.720 align:middle line:84%
more energy than we
ever have in the past.

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:46.140 align:middle line:84%
How long can we do that
before our simulation is full?

00:19:46.140 --> 00:19:48.660 align:middle line:90%
Before the storage device--

00:19:48.660 --> 00:19:50.110 align:middle line:90%
I don't think it's a hard drive.

00:19:50.110 --> 00:19:53.820 align:middle line:84%
I think we will have transcended
the hard drives by the time

00:19:53.820 --> 00:19:56.460 align:middle line:90%
the simulation is understood.

00:19:56.460 --> 00:19:58.920 align:middle line:84%
But whatever it is that's
generating this information,

00:19:58.920 --> 00:20:00.470 align:middle line:90%
how much energy can it hold?

00:20:00.470 --> 00:20:03.510 align:middle line:90%


00:20:03.510 --> 00:20:06.400 align:middle line:84%
So, for the first
time in human history,

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:09.480 align:middle line:84%
we have a reason to question
how much information can we

00:20:09.480 --> 00:20:13.620 align:middle line:84%
generate and store in the
field that connects all things

00:20:13.620 --> 00:20:16.924 align:middle line:84%
before that field
actually reaches capacity.

00:20:16.924 --> 00:20:18.090 align:middle line:10%
I don't know the answer now.

00:20:18.090 --> 00:20:21.600 align:middle line:10%
But I think we're going to
find out within our lifetimes.

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:26.070 align:middle line:84%
The very fact that we
are in a simulation

00:20:26.070 --> 00:20:28.770 align:middle line:84%
tells us something
very, very powerful.

00:20:28.770 --> 00:20:32.700 align:middle line:84%
It tells us because we are
here that we are either near

00:20:32.700 --> 00:20:35.100 align:middle line:84%
or that we've already
reached a place

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:38.820 align:middle line:84%
in our evolutionary process
where we need a simulation.

00:20:38.820 --> 00:20:41.480 align:middle line:84%
We were already at
a place where we

00:20:41.480 --> 00:20:44.930 align:middle line:84%
need to find a new way of
being, a new way of living,

00:20:44.930 --> 00:20:47.030 align:middle line:90%
a new way of thinking.

00:20:47.030 --> 00:20:50.460 align:middle line:84%
Now it may be because
of a climate change.

00:20:50.460 --> 00:20:53.070 align:middle line:84%
Maybe we are an
advanced civilization.

00:20:53.070 --> 00:20:56.150 align:middle line:84%
We are an advanced
society living right here

00:20:56.150 --> 00:20:59.420 align:middle line:84%
on planet Earth or
maybe some other world.

00:20:59.420 --> 00:21:02.730 align:middle line:84%
And we've experienced
climate change.

00:21:02.730 --> 00:21:06.000 align:middle line:84%
And we did not know
